Return :class:`Regex` with an attached parse action to transform the parsed result as if called using `re.sub(expr, repl, string) `_. Example:: make_html = Regex(r"(\w+):(.*?):").sub(r"<\1>\2") print(make_html.transform_string("h1:main title:")) # prints "

main title

"
Child classes must define this method, which defines how the ``default_name`` is set.

Token for matching strings that match a given regular expression. Defined with string specifying the regular expression in a form recognized by the stdlib Python `re module <https://docs.python.org/3/library/re.html>`_. If the given regex contains named groups (defined using ``(?P<name>...)``), these will be preserved as named :class:`ParseResults`.
If instead of the Python stdlib ``re`` module you wish to use a different RE module (such as the ``regex`` module), you can do so by building your ``Regex`` object with a compiled RE that was compiled using ``regex``.
Example::
realnum = Regex(r"[+-]?\d+\.\d*") # ref: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/267399/how-do-you-match-only-valid-roman-numerals-with-a-regular-expression roman = Regex(r"M{0,4}(CM|CD|D?{0,3})(XC|XL|L?X{0,3})(IX|IV|V?I{0,3})")
# named fields in a regex will be returned as named results date = Regex(r'(?P<year>\d{4})-(?P<month>\d\d?)-(?P<day>\d\d?)')
# the Regex class will accept re's compiled using the regex module import regex parser = pp.Regex(regex.compile(r'[0-9]'))
